HEADWORD: Elench
<hw>E*lench"</hw> <pr>(⟦esl⟧*l⟦ecr⟧⟦nsm⟧k")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Elenchs</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L.
<ets>elenchus</ets>, Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ to convict, confute, prove: cf.
OF. <ets>elenche</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Logic)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>That
part of an argument on which its conclusiveness depends; that which
convinces of refutes an antagonist; a refutation.</def> <sd>(b)</sd>
<def>A specious but fallacious argument; a sophism.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Elenchical</ent>⟦br⟧
